<DOC><DOCNO> AP900226-0007 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-26-90 0042EST</FILEID><FIRST>r w PM-ASNE-Winners     02-26 0226</FIRST><SECOND>PM-ASNE-Winners,0233</SECOND><HEAD>ASNE Names Five National Journalism Winners</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The American Society of Newspaper Editors hasannounced five winners of its 1989 Distinguished Writing Awards.   The journalists, selected from among 500 applicants, willreceive cash awards of $2,500 each during the ASNE's annualconvention, April 3-6.   The winners, announced Sunday, are:   _ Terrie Claflin, staff writer for the Medford (Ore.) MailTribune for non-deadline writing. Claflin wrote four stories thatchronicled the short life of a brain-damaged foster child whosebiological mother is a drug addict.   _ Diana Griego Erwin, columnist for the Orange County Register,Santa Ana, Calif., for commentary and column writing. Her columnsincluded one about a Hispanic laborer who had difficulty getting adriver's license because of his poor English.   _ Samuel Francis, The Washington Times, for editorial writing.Some of the editorials written by Francis, who won the award forthe second straight year, focused on conservative themes such assupport for legislation establishing a review process for theNational Endowment for the Arts.   _ Linnet Myers, reporter for the Chicago Tribune, state andlocal government reporting. Myers wrote a three-part seriesreviewing the parade of people through Chicago's criminal courtsystem.   _ David Von Drehle, reporter for the Miami Herald, deadlinewriting. Von Drehle was cited for his first-person account ofHurricane Hugo's assault on Charleston, S.C.</TEXT></DOC>